### 8b. GitHub Issue command (ready to copy-paste)

> **Do NOT run this command yourself.** The user creates the issue manually.

After the report, output a fenced code block labeled **`GITHUB ISSUE`**
with a single `gh issue create` command the user can copy-paste.

**Label mapping:**

| Severity | Labels |
|----------|--------|
| Critical | `bug`, `severity:critical`, `priority:p0` |
| High     | `bug`, `severity:high`, `priority:p1` |
| Medium   | `bug`, `severity:medium`, `priority:p2` |
| Low      | `bug`, `severity:low`, `priority:p3` |

If a label doesn't exist yet in the repo, `gh` will fail. To handle this,
output the label-creation commands **above** the issue-creation command,
using `2>/dev/null || true` so they silently skip if the label already
exists.

**Issue title format:**
`fix(<scope>): <short description>` — reuse the exact commit subject line
so the issue and commit are searchable together.

**Issue body format (GitHub-flavored Markdown):**
Use the template below. Fill in all placeholders from the report above.

```bash
# ── Create labels if they don't exist yet ────────────
gh label create "bug" --color "d73a4a" --description "Something isn't working" 2>/dev/null || true
gh label create "<severity-label>" --color "<color>" --description "<description>" 2>/dev/null || true
gh label create "<priority-label>" --color "<color>" --description "<description>" 2>/dev/null || true

# ── Create the bug-fix issue ─────────────────────────
gh issue create \
  --title "fix(<scope>): <short description>" \
  --label "bug,<severity-label>,<priority-label>" \
  --body "$(cat <<'ISSUE_EOF'
## Bug Fix Report

**Bug ID:** `<BUG-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN>`
**Severity:** <Critical|High|Medium|Low>
**Status:** ✅ Fixed & Verified

---

