### 8c. Append to CSV bug log

After every bug fix, **the agent updates** `docs/bugs/bug-log.csv` by appending
one row with the bug details. If the file doesn't exist yet, create it with the
header row first. This is part of the fix automation and should be completed
before the user reviews and commits.

**CSV columns (in this exact order):**

| # | Column | Source | Format |
|---|--------|--------|--------|
| 1 | `bug_id` | Phase 8a | `BUG-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN` |
| 2 | `date` | Current date | `YYYY-MM-DD` |
| 3 | `severity` | Phase 8a | `critical\|high\|medium\|low` |
| 4 | `priority` | Phase 8b label mapping | `p0\|p1\|p2\|p3` |
| 5 | `scope` | Commit scope | kebab-case (e.g. `auth`, `data-grid`) |
| 6 | `error_message` | Phase 1 | The raw error — escape inner quotes by doubling them |
| 7 | `location` | Phase 1 | `file:line` |
| 8 | `root_cause` | Phase 1 | One sentence |
| 9 | `trigger` | Phase 1 | What input/state caused it |
| 10 | `files_changed` | Phase 3 | Semicolon-separated list of paths |
| 11 | `approach` | Phase 2 | One sentence summary of the fix |
| 12 | `risk_level` | Phase 2 | `low\|medium\|high` |
| 13 | `breaking_change` | Phase 7 | `yes\|no` |
| 14 | `prevention_mechanism` | Phase 4 | `type-guard\|zod-schema\|assertion\|lint-rule\|env-check` (semicolon-separated if multiple) |
| 15 | `prevention_details` | Phase 4 | What was added |
| 16 | `new_tests` | Phase 5 | Integer |
| 17 | `updated_tests` | Phase 5 | Integer |
| 18 | `total_tests` | Phase 5 | Integer (full suite count) |
| 19 | `type_check` | Phase 5 | `pass\|fail` |
| 20 | `lint` | Phase 5 | `pass\|fail` |
| 21 | `commit_type` | Phase 7 | `fix\|feat\|fix!\|feat!` |
| 22 | `release_type` | Phase 7 | `patch\|minor\|major` |
| 23 | `commit_message` | Phase 7 | Full subject line |
| 24 | `github_issue` | Phase 8b | `pending` (user fills after running gh command) |
| 25 | `follow_ups` | Phase 8a | Semicolon-separated list |

**Output format:**

Update `docs/bugs/bug-log.csv` directly by appending a new row with all the
values from the bug fix phases. Create the file with the header row if it
doesn't exist yet. All values must be double-quoted. Escape any internal
double quotes by doubling them (`""`). Replace literal newlines with ` | `
so the CSV stays single-line per row.

**Implementation:**

1. Check if `docs/bugs/bug-log.csv` exists. If not, create it with the header row.
2. Append a single CSV row with all 25 columns in the exact order specified above.
3. Ensure all fields are double-quoted and internal quotes are escaped as `""`.
4. Use `;` as the delimiter for multi-value fields (files_changed, prevention_mechanism, follow_ups).
5. The `github_issue` column should be `"pending"` — the user updates it manually after creating the GitHub issue.
6. Do NOT output a shell command to the user; instead, use the StrReplace or Write tool to update the file directly.

**Important rules when updating the CSV:**

- Double-quote every field — no exceptions.
- If a field value contains double quotes, escape them as `""`.
- If a field value contains commas, newlines, or special characters, the
  double-quoting handles it — but replace literal newlines with ` | ` so the
  CSV stays single-line per row.
- Multi-value fields (files_changed, prevention_mechanism, follow_ups) use
  semicolons as the internal delimiter.
- The `github_issue` column is always `"pending"` — the user updates it
  manually after running the `gh issue create` command (with the issue URL
  or number).
- Include `docs/bugs/bug-log.csv` in the `git add` command from Phase 7
  (add it to the explicit file list) since it is now automatically updated.

